---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base>

<div class="page">

  <p class="eyebrow">A framework · Michael Borck</p>
  <h1 class="title">Conversation, not Delegation.</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">A framework for using AI as a collaborator, not a delegate.</p>

  <section class="manifesto">
    <p class="lead">
      The dominant pattern of AI use in professional work is delegation. A problem
      arrives. The work is handed to a model. A polished result comes back. The
      work appears to be done.
    </p>
    <p>
      The cost of this pattern is not in the output. The output is often serviceable.
      The cost is in what stops happening in the head of the person who used to do
      the work — the small, quiet, judgment-forming activity that used to happen
      between problem and answer, and that is the actual substance of professional
      practice.
    </p>
    <p>
      Conversation is the alternative posture. Conversing with an AI is not the same
      as asking it for an answer. It is brainstorming with it, ideating against it,
      interacting with the output it produces, pushing back when it produces something
      that looks plausible but is wrong. The work that used to happen quietly stays
      where it should: in the head of the practitioner, with the model as a counterpart
      rather than a substitute.
    </p>
    <p>
      Conversation preserves judgment. Delegation outsources it. The distinction is
      not philosophical. It is operational, and it is the difference between a firm
      whose use of AI strengthens its practice and one whose use quietly hollows it out.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr class="section-divider" />

  <p class="section-eyebrow">The four moves</p>

  <div class="moves">
    <div class="move">
      <div class="move-name"><span class="num">01</span>Brainstorm</div>
      <p class="move-desc">
        Use the model to widen the field. Ask for the obvious answer, then the
        non-obvious one, then the one nobody has considered. The aim is not the
        right answer; it is to see the shape of the question more fully than you
        could alone.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="move">
      <div class="move-name"><span class="num">02</span>Ideate</div>
      <p class="move-desc">
        Take the most promising thread and develop it. Have the model produce
        variations, alternatives, opposing positions. Treat its output as raw
        material to react to, not an answer to accept.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="move">
      <div class="move-name"><span class="num">03</span>Interact</div>
      <p class="move-desc">
        Engage with what the model produces. Ask it to defend its claims, to
        articulate its reasoning, to make its assumptions explicit. The interaction
        is where your judgment forms, because you cannot interrogate something
        without deciding what to interrogate.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="move">
      <div class="move-name"><span class="num">04</span>Pushback</div>
      <p class="move-desc">
        Disagree, on substance. The model is wrong often, in subtle ways, in ways
        that look plausible. Pushing back is the move that keeps you from
        accepting the polished output as truth and forces the model to either
        improve its case or concede the point.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="section-divider" />

  <p class="section-eyebrow">The books</p>

  <div class="books">
    <a class="book" href="https://books.borck.education">
      <div class="book-title">Conversation not Delegation</div>
      <div class="book-desc">
        The framework in detail — the four moves, the principles, the
        practical applications.
      </div>
    </a>
    <a class="book" href="https://books.borck.education">
      <div class="book-title">Partner Don't Police</div>
      <div class="book-desc">
        Applying the framework in a teaching context. Adopted onto the reading
        list at Kaplan Business School.
      </div>
    </a>
  </div>

  <p style="font-family: var(--font-sans); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--gray-1); line-height: 1.6; margin-top: 1.5rem; text-align: center;">
